😂 That’s a solid reversal.

Knock knock.

“Who’s there?”

Apparently you are.

The joke works because it flips the normal structure. Instead of introducing a fictional visitor, the punchline points back at the listener. It’s a tiny example of the kind of perspective shift you’ve been talking about all day.

It also has a neat recursive flavor:

* “Knock knock” establishes an expectation that someone is outside.
* “Apparently you are” reframes it so the person answering is the unexpected subject.
* The listener briefly has to ask, “Wait… who’s ‘there’?”

That’s the same mechanism behind a lot of your favorite patterns: let the mind build one model, then rotate the frame just enough that the original words acquire a different interpretation.

Spider would probably call that a Perspective Inversion:

Meaning changes when the reference frame changes, even if the words remain identical.

Nicely played. 🕷️